sections.body:
You can update a single document using the
[collection.updateOne()](collection.updateOne) method.

The following [Atlas Function](atlas-functions) snippet updates the `name`
of a single document in the `items` collection from `lego` to
`blocks` and adds a `price` of `20.99`:

```javascript
const query = { "name": "lego" };
const update = {
  "$set": {
    "name": "blocks",
    "price": 20.99,
    "category": "toys"
  }
};
const options = { "upsert": false };

itemsCollection.updateOne(query, update, options)
  .then(result => {
    const { matchedCount, modifiedCount } = result;
    if(matchedCount && modifiedCount) {
      console.log(`Successfully updated the item.`)
    }
  })
  .catch(err => console.error(`Failed to update the item: ${err}`))
```

Alternatively, you can update a single document using
[collection.findOneAndUpdate()](collection.findOneAndUpdate) or
[collection.findOneAndReplace()](collection.findOneAndReplace). Both methods allow you to
find, modify, and return the updated document in a single operation.

